<handout xml:id="handout-section-2-8-subspaces">
  <title>2.8 Subspaces</title>

  <page xml:id="p-2-8-objectives">
    <title>Overview</title>

    <objectives xml:id="obj-2-8-topics-goals">
      <title>Topics</title>
      <ul>
        <li>Subspaces, column space, and null space.</li>
        <li>A basis for a subspace.</li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>
    <objectives>
      <title>Goals</title>
      <ul>
        <li>Determine whether a set is a subspace.</li>
        <li>Determine whether a vector is in a particular subspace, or find a vector in that subspace.</li>
        <li>Construct a basis for a subspace (e.g., a basis for <m>\operatorname{Col}(A)</m>).</li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>

      <p><em>Motivating Question</em>: Given a matrix <m>A</m>, what is the set of vectors <m>\vec b</m> for which we can solve
        <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m>?
      </p>

      <p><nbsp/></p>

    <definition xml:id="def-subset-rn">
      <title>Subset of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m></title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>subset of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m></term> is any collection of vectors contained in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <definition xml:id="def-subspace">
      <title>Subspace</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A subset <m>H</m> of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> is a <term>subspace</term> if:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><m>c\vec u\in H</m> for any scalar <m>c\in\mathbb{R}</m> and any <m>\vec u\in H</m>.</li>
          <li><m>\vec u+\vec v\in H</m> for all <m>\vec u,\vec v\in H</m>.</li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Note that scalar closure implies the zero vector must be in <m>H</m>.
    </p>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <example xml:id="ex-subspace-pictures" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Which of the following subsets could be subspaces of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>?</p>

        <image xml:id="img-subspaces" source="./subspaces.png" width="80%">
          <shortdescription>A graphic showing three subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>. The first is the unit square. The second is a line through the origin. The third is a line that does not pass throught the origin.</shortdescription>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </example> 
    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>

  <page xml:id="p-2-8-subspace-examples">
    <title>Examples of Subspaces</title>
    <example>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                For each subset of <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m> given below, determine if it is a subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task workspace="0.8in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\left\{\vec 0\right\}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task workspace="0.8in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\left\{\vec 0, \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix},\begin{bmatrix}-1 \\ 0 \\ -1\end{bmatrix} \right\}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task workspace="0.8in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\left\{\begin{bmatrix}1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\right\}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task workspace="0.8in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\textrm{Span}\left\{\begin{bmatrix}1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}\right\}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task workspace="true">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\left\{\begin{bmatrix} x \\ -x \\ y \end{bmatrix}; x,y\in\mathbb{R}\right\}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </example>
    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-2-8-col-null-definition">
    <title>The Column Space and Null Space</title>

    <p>
      Recall that for vectors <m>\vec v_1,\dots,\vec v_p\in\mathbb{R}^n</m>,
      <m>\operatorname{Span}\{\vec v_1,\dots,\vec v_p\}</m> is the subspace consisting of all linear combinations of these vectors. Not only is the span of vectors an example of a subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, they are the only examples of subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
    </p>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-subspace-are-span">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Every subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> can be written as the span of a finite number of vectors; that is, if <m>H</m> is a subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>, then there exists vectors <m>\vec v_1, \dots, \vec v_k</m> so that <m>H = \textrm{Span}\left\{\vec v_1, \dots, \vec v_n\right\}</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </theorem>
    

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <definition xml:id="def-col-null">
      <title>Column Space and Null Space</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A=\begin{bmatrix}\vec a_1 \amp \cdots \amp \vec a_n\end{bmatrix}</m> be
          an <m>m\times n</m> matrix.
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            The <term>column space</term> of <m>A</m>,
            <m>\operatorname{Col}(A)</m>, is the subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^m</m>
            spanned by <m>\vec a_1,\dots,\vec a_n</m>.
          </li>

          <li>
            The <term>null space</term> of <m>A</m>,
            <m>\operatorname{Nul}(A)</m>, is the subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>
            consisting of all solutions to <m>A\vec x=\vec 0</m>.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <example xml:id="ex-colspace-membership" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Is <m>\vec b</m> in the column space of <m>A</m>?</p>

        <me>
          A=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp -3 \amp -4\\
            -4 \amp 6 \amp -2\\
            -3 \amp 7 \amp 6
          \end{bmatrix}
          \sim
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp -3 \amp -4\\
            0 \amp -6 \amp -18\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          \vec b=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            3\\3\\-4
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-2-8-basis-definition">
    <title>Basis</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-nullspace-membership" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine whether
          <m>\vec v</m> is in <m>\operatorname{Nul}(A)</m>. 
          <me>A = \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp -3 \amp -4\\
            -4 \amp 6 \amp -2\\
            -3 \amp 7 \amp 6
          \end{bmatrix} \sim
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp -3 \amp -4\\
            0 \amp -6 \amp -18\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix}, 
          \qquad          
          \vec v=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            -5\lambda\\
            -3\lambda\\
            \lambda
          \end{bmatrix},
          \quad \lambda\in\mathbb{R}.
        </me>
    </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>

  <page>
    <title>Definition of basis and Example</title>
        <definition xml:id="def-basis" workspace="1in">
      <title>Basis</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <em>basis</em> for a subspace <m>H</m> is a set of linearly independent vectors in
          <m>H</m> that span <m>H</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>    
    <p><nbsp/></p>
    
<example xml:id="ex-basis-subspace" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let
        </p>

        <me>
          H=\left\{
          \begin{bmatrix}
            x_1\\x_2\\x_3\\x_4
          \end{bmatrix}
          \in\mathbb{R}^4\;\middle|\;
          x_1+2x_2+x_3+5x_4=0
          \right\}.
        </me>

        <ol marker="a">
          <li>Find a matrix <m>A</m> such that <m>H=\operatorname{Nul}(A)</m>.</li>
          <li>Construct a basis for <m>H</m>.</li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-2-8-example-basis-col-null">
    <title>Example: Basis for Column Space and Null Space</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-basis-col-null" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Construct a basis for <m>\operatorname{Nul}(A)</m> and <m>\operatorname{Col}(A)</m>.</p>

        <me>
          A=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            -3 \amp 6 \amp -1 \amp 0\\
            1 \amp -2 \amp 2 \amp 0\\
            2 \amp -4 \amp 5 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix}
          \sim
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p><nbsp/></p>

    
  </page>

